<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900716-0155</DOCNO><DOCID>900716-0155.</DOCID><HL>   Study Says Gains   In Pay to Exceed   Inflation in '91   ----   By Robin Goldwyn Blumenthal   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>07/16/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5A</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><IN>ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Pay raises in the U.S. will outpace inflationnext year more than any time in the past three years, asurvey by the Conference Board found.   The Conference Board, an independent business researchgroup, said pay increases for U.S. salaried workers willaverage about 5% this year and are expected to rise to anaverage of nearly 5.5% in 1991. The findings were made in theboard's annual private-sector salary survey, which covers 537companies in various industries.</LP><TEXT>   The board's current projection for the rise in inflationfor 1991 is 4.5%, while pay increases for exempt employeesare expected to rise to 5.5%. Exempt employees are workerssuch as salaried professionals and supervisors who areexcluded from overtime provisions of the federal wage andsalary laws.   The report noted salary increases would be greatest in thediversified services and insurance industries, with gainsaveraging about 5.5% this year and 5.6% in 1991. Wholesaleand retail trade companies reported the lowest salaryincreases, averaging 5% both this year and next. Averageincreases for nonexecutive salaried workers in manufacturingwill be 5% in 1990 and slightly higher next year.   Executives will receive slightly higher pay increases thanother salaried workers both this year and next, withincreases averaging 5.5%.   Of the companies surveyed, 82% are using at least onevariable pay program, the board said. Eligibility forvariable compensation that once was mostly limited toexecutive and sales personnel is now being extended to otheremployee groups, the board said.   The variable pay programs &quot;provide an alternative to fixedsalary costs while enabling employers to foster, enhance andreward various forms of achievement,&quot; said ElizabethArreglado, Conference Board compensation specialist.   The most popular form of variable pay is special cashawards for outstanding individual contributions, which wasused by 38% of those polled. About 30% offer incentive payfor employees who reach specific performance goals; 29% userecognition programs; 27% have current pay profit-sharingplans; 23% give lump-sum merit awards; 18% offer teamincentives; 11% have gain-sharing and skill-based payprograms; and 6% have two-tier pay plans.</TEXT></DOC>